---

# Active Directory IAM Home Lab

## Overview

This project documents my hands-on Identity and Access Management (IAM) home lab built using VirtualBox and Windows Server 2022. The goal of this lab is to simulate real-world IAM tasks such as user provisioning, group management, password policy enforcement, and authentication monitoring using Active Directory.

---

# Lab Environment

Host Machine
Windows 11 laptop

Virtualization Software
Oracle VirtualBox

Server Operating System
Windows Server 2022 Standard Evaluation (Desktop Experience)

Directory Service
Active Directory Domain Services (AD DS)

Domain Name
corp.local

Server Role
Domain Controller

---

# What is VirtualBox?

VirtualBox is a virtualization platform that allows multiple operating systems to run on a single computer.

In this lab, VirtualBox is used to simulate a corporate network environment by running a Windows Server virtual machine inside my main computer.

This allows safe testing and experimentation without affecting the host system.

---

# What is a Domain Controller?

A Domain Controller is a server that manages authentication and access control within a network.

The Domain Controller is responsible for:

• verifying user logins
• managing user accounts
• controlling password policies
• enforcing security policies
• managing access to network resources

In this lab, the Windows Server VM was promoted to a Domain Controller for the domain:

corp.local

---

# What is Active Directory?

Active Directory is Microsoft’s directory service used to manage identities and access within a network.

Active Directory stores information about:

• users
• computers
• groups
• permissions
• security policies

It allows administrators to centrally control authentication and authorization across the organization.

---

# Identity and Access Management Concepts Practiced

This lab focuses on core IAM concepts including:

User provisioning
Creating new user accounts in Active Directory

Authentication
Verifying user identity during login

Authorization
Controlling what resources a user can access

Role-Based Access Control (RBAC)
Assigning permissions through security groups

Least Privilege
Giving users only the access necessary for their role

Account Lifecycle Management
Creating, modifying, disabling, and removing user accounts

